ripped
in
half.
Meera
unearthed
a
crock
of
honey
and
a
big
sack
of
apples.
Outside,
they
made
their
farewells.
Rickon
sobbed
and
clung
to
HodorвЂ™s
leg
until
Osha
gave
him
a
smack
with
the
butt
end
of
her
spear.
Then
he
followed
her
quick
enough.
Shaggydog
stalked
after
them.
The
last
Bran
saw
of
them
was
the
direwolfвЂ™s
tail
as
it
vanished
behind
the
broken
tower.

The
iron
portcullis
that
closed
the
HunterвЂ™s
Gate
had
been
warped
so
badly
by
heat
it
could
not
be
raised
more
than
a
foot.
They
had
to
squeeze
beneath
its
spikes,
one
by
one.

вЂњWill
we
go
to
your
lord
father?вЂќ
Bran
asked
as
they
crossed
the
drawbridge
between
the
walls.
вЂњTo
Greywater
Watch?вЂќ

Meera
looked
to
her
brother
for
the
answer.
вЂњOur
road
is
north,вЂќ
Jojen
announced.

At
the
edge
of
the
wolfswood,
Bran
turned
in
his
basket
for
one
last
glimpse
of
the
castle
that
had
been
his
life.
Wisps
of
smoke
still
rose
into
the
grey
sky,
but
no
more
than
might
have
risen
from
WinterfellвЂ™s
chimneys
on
a
cold
autumn
afternoon.
Soot
stains
marked
some
of
the
arrow
loops,
and
here
and
there
a
crack
or
a
missing
merlon
could
be
seen
in
the
curtain
wall,
but
it
seemed
little
enough
from
this
distance.
Beyond,
the
tops
of
the
keeps
and
towers
still
stood
as
they
had
for
hundreds
of
years,
and
it
was
hard
to
tell
that
the
castle
had
been
sacked
and
burned
at
all.
The
stone
is
strong,
Bran
told
himself,
the
roots
of
the
trees
go
deep,
and
under
the
ground
the
Kings
of
Winter
sit
their
thrones.
So
long
as
those
remained,
Winterfell
remained.
It
was
not
dead,
just
broken.
Like
me,
he
thought.
IвЂ™m
not
dead
either.





